public float speed = 5.0f; // Speed at which the objects move up.
public float spawnRate = 1.0f; // Time in seconds between spawns.
public GameObject[] objectsToSpawn; // An array of objects to spawn.

private float nextSpawnTime = 0.0f; // Time of the next spawn.

void Update() {
    if (Time.time > nextSpawnTime) {
        // Reset the next spawn time.
        nextSpawnTime = Time.time + spawnRate;

        // Instantiate a random object from the array.
        GameObject objectToSpawn = objectsToSpawn[Random.Range(0, objectsToSpawn.Length)];
        Instantiate(objectToSpawn, new Vector3(Random.Range(-5.0f, 5.0f), -5.0f, 0.0f), Quaternion.identity);
    }

    // Move all objects up.
    foreach (GameObject obj in GameObject.FindGameObjectsWithTag("MovingObject")) {
        obj.transform.position += Vector3.up * Time.deltaTime * speed;
    }
}
```

In this code, the `Update()` function is called every frame. It checks if enough time has passed since the last spawn, and if so, instantiates a random object from the `objectsToSpawn` array at a random position along the x-axis and a fixed position along the y-axis. It then sets the time of the next spawn to be `spawnRate` seconds after the current time.

The code then moves all objects tagged as "MovingObject" up the screen at a rate of `speed` units per second. You can change the speed and spawn rate values to get the desired effect.

